##Seven Chinese tell of the "war epidemic" in the United States, Japan, Iran and Italy

Micro-signal, Rancaijing

A feature presentation, a daily in depth report, redefines the innovation economy.

"Bistro" is the story column of Burning Finance and Economics. It tells the true story of life in the age of innovation economy. This is the 33rd issue.

Author | Kong ming-ming, Zhao Lei, Yan Lijiao, Wei Jia, Jin Fan

Editor | Zhou Changfan

According to the World Health Organization (WHO) definition, "global pandemic" is a "worldwide, widespread human-to-human new disease. In the early hours of March 12 Beijing Time, the World Health Organization (who) qualified the new coronavirus epidemic and declared that the 2019 coronavirus epidemic had escalated from "epidemic" to "global pandemic" .

World Health Organization Director General Tan Desai said that in the past two weeks, the number of 2019 coronavirus infections outside China has increased 13-fold and the number of affected countries has tripled. The outbreak is currently occurring in 114 countries and regions, and the number of confirmed cases, deaths and affected countries are expected to rise further in the coming weeks.

Panic is spreading to every corner of the world. What happened to the Chinese scattered around the world in the wake of the global pandemic? How did they cope? What are the specific circumstances of the countries in which they live?

((PW)) , the Chinese in the seven countries where the epidemic is serious, we can see from their eyes that, every country has its own culture and system, from the initial lack of attention to "tight security" , from the initial lack of attention to protection to the inability to buy masks, from the initial insouciance to the hoarding of supplies and even to the purchase of guns, from the initial fluke to panic flight, each country has made its own defensive choices, and this is a catastrophe that the world needs to face together.

"We still need to look at the disaster rationally, because similar things have happened in history. We still need to be calm, objective and optimistic, and we also need to be prepared for long-term difficulties, " said one interviewee.

Ten thousand Marathon could bring an outbreak

A lot of people are buying guns for disaster

Sun Linjia, entrepreneur, 362008 East West Bank Classic – Doubles

I work in the 2008 East West Bank Classic – Doubles and have no plans to return home for the time being. Now I will keep track of the California epidemic information, many friends will also be in the friend circle retweets.

When things got bad at home, I thought it was only a matter of time before the epidemic spread to the rest of the world. Common Sense tells us that this emerging infectious virus has a high probability of reaching the world before a vaccine is available. And it's not quite as global as it was in 2003.

I haven't felt how much importance the United States has attached to this issue in national policy, and it has only been for the last two weeks. Last week or so, the governor of California said it was a sign of public policy to start testing for free. Schools distribute hand sanitizer and other preventive measures such as washing hands frequently and not going to crowded places. I also received a notice of possession of my residence on March 12.

I think public policies and measures are far from enough. But unlike in the United States and China, where the Chinese may be used to acting in concert after the Macroeconomic regulation and control policy comes out, there will be a lot of people who will say no if the U.S. government issues measures that require people to wear face masks, this violates personal freedom, so some measures they really have no way to implement, can only advocate.

Now a lot of supplies are starting to run short, and more people are wearing masks on the road. This week is different from last week. Recently, I will receive a phone call or wechat every day, asking me how things are going here, let me pay attention to safety. Since last week, my parents have asked me to punch a card in the wechat group every day, to post a video every two days, and to store more grain at home, not to go out for a month, to wear a mask and so on.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
March 14th versus a week ago

Source / Interviewee, Walmart, Los Angeles

On the economic side, I think the main impact will be on consumption, for example, people will be less likely to be in shopping malls, restaurants, scenic spots, and many people will also be less likely to have meetings and travel. Some friends said they downloaded many apps to deliver food, and they used them much more frequently than before.

According to friends, a lot of people started buying guns in Self-defense two weeks ago. Because when there are major disasters in American history, rioters may break into people's homes and rob them. Many of them don't really trust the government or the police to protect people when something like that happens.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
People go to the source of the gun / interviewee

Last Sunday, more than 100,000 people in more than 20 countries, more than 50 states, ran a marathon in Los Angeles, which I think is likely to spread the virus. Since last Sunday, I have been stockpiling food at home, not going out at all, ready to wait for two weeks to see the details of the situation to consider.

Target, LOS ANGELES, March 14

But I personally think it's important to be rational about disasters, because there have been similar events in history. We should remain calm, objective and optimistic, and at the same time be prepared to face long-term difficulties.

Until the whole country is shut down

That's when people really care

Dylan, international student, 22, Florence, Italy

In the last two months, I've been traveling back and forth between Italy and China, like I've been through two outbreaks.

On January 10, I returned from Florence to my hometown in Shandong Province. A few days later, the outbreak broke out. The whole Spring Festival, the domestic situation is grim, at that time, I think Italy is safer, so on February 5 flew back. I just got off the plane, took off my mask, and breathed like a baby, but then, 14 days after I was quarantined at home, there was an outbreak in Italy, and I was in another outbreak.

Unlike China's rigid defenses, the people here are business as usual. Coffee Shops, bars, restaurants, and entertainment venues are open for business, with morning runs, dog walks, parties and the like. We have a confirmed case at our school, and classes are still open. If you don't watch the News, you won't even know the virus is spreading.

I only go out twice a week to buy groceries. To be honest, it takes courage to wear a mask outside. I went to a bar across the street from the supermarket. Once, a group of people at a party stared at me and my girlfriend, thinking we were different. "If you don't feel sick, you don't need to wear a mask, " said another old woman.

And I don't feel their fear. Italian students said that this is a "heavy cold" , the death of the elderly. The less people around me care, the more I worry, because if they don't, it's hard to control. And medical resources are limited, once the infection, we are not citizens, whether to get timely treatment is also an issue.

I wanted to stock up on supplies and not go out, but on March 7th there were more than 1,200 new cases a day in Italy, and in the Emilia region, the second worst affected region, there were people playing basketball on the streets and basking in the sun. I just want to say two words: Awesome. I immediately decided to go back home and booked a flight the next day through the travel agency. At that time the ticket had already started to rise in price, usually 2,800 yuan can buy the ticket, I spent 4,600 yuan, connecting flight from Dubai, flew 17 hours. Along the way, I never took off my mask, even did not dare to drink a sip of water.

As soon as I left, the city of Milan was sealed off. On March 10, Italy's cumulative confirmed cases broke 10,000. I think this is a turning point, from that day on, Italy "the whole country closed the city" , we really pay attention to it.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
People Queue outside a supermarket in Florence March 12

A sealed order announced that the price of return tickets immediately increased, economy class seconds, tens of thousands of yuan a ticket to rely on robbery. We have a wechat group of the "Epidemic Return Team" , and we can clearly feel that everyone's mood is getting more and more impatient, in recent days, the most frequently asked question is "can I fly today? " One of my classmates bought a ticket from Moscow to transfer back to China on the 22nd, and now I do not know if I can fly.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Group chat screen shot of "Epidemic Return Team"

From the photos sent by my classmates, the streets are indeed empty now. I am learning the Chinese experience by driving a car and shouting at people not to go out. However, Italians have always been free, will not be so "obedient" , so no matter how the blockade, certainly will not be as strict as China, you just need to fill out a similar pass-like self-declaration at any time, or can go out.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A post office in Florence limits traffic on March 12

Citizens fill out forms on the streets

Now I am quarantined in the hometown hotel, this half year's study is a delay. The teacher will provide PPT and online classes for us to self-study, will also send email assignments, but I am very worried about the test will not pass. Italy's schools will be closed until April 3rd, hopefully by then everyone will be able to take off their masks and breathe freely.

The activities of 999 people are continuing

Chinese wearing masks will be discriminated against

Dirk, 27, medical technology worker, Hamburg, Germany

I finished my master's degree in Germany and have been working there for nine years now, since 2011. The situation in Germany is very bad, the national level is not sensitive enough to the epidemic, related measures are lagging behind.

After the Italian epidemic spread, Germany did not block and Italy's exchanges, did not learn the domestic experience of epidemic prevention. After the discovery of the case in Germany, Carnival, parties, parades, ball games and so on are continuing, tens of thousands of people kept to create.

Some of these moves are a bit of a stretch. Two or three days ago, the states announced "more than 1000 people all kinds of activities prohibited. ". In other words, the 999 continued as usual. Some university libraries have a maximum capacity of 350 people on the same day. Where the numbers come from, I don't know.

When the outbreak began to spread, authorities even told the public through the media, the fight against the virus by washing hands frequently, wearing masks useless. Our judgment on this message is that there is a shortage of materials on the market that can not support all people to wear masks, and that is the only way the authorities can appease the people.

But there are early signs, as early as the outbreak in China, I was in the circle of students abroad are buying protective supplies, donated to the domestic, European countries are clearly not ready to deal with the virus. When the Burger first appeared, the store sold out of face masks and disinfectant overnight. I don't know if it's Chinese or foreign.

Meanwhile, authorities are telling the public that between 60 and 70 percent of the German population will be infected.

The explanation given by the local medical school and doctors is that no European country, including Germany, can follow China's massive measures to close the cities, and they need to find a balance between the national economy and the fight against the virus, so since they can't control the virus in a short time, they want to slow the spread of the virus to control the disease.

It will eventually affect 60-70% of the population, but as long as the front lines are long enough, say 100-200 new cases a day, the system has enough beds and doctors to cope.

Clearly, reality has shattered their assumptions. The News on the evening of the 12th German time was that more than 1000 new cases were confirmed in a single day, which could be said to be the beginning of an outbreak.

But now the streets of Hamburg are still bustling, Chinese people are relatively strong sense of self-protection, go out will wear a mask, Germans, on the contrary, no one wear a mask, and very calm. They didn't realize it at first, but even if they did, the N95 masks on the market have gone from $5 to $15, and they can't be bought.

Many European countries have "anti-hijab" laws, which prohibit the wearing of veils in public places, to protect against terrorists. This law has a deep-rooted influence on some particularly bigoted people in Germany, especially the elderly. If you wear a mask in public, people will look at you, and they won't understand why you're wearing a mask.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Hamburg School Announces Class suspension. Source / interviewee

The latest news is that schools in Hamburg will be closed from next Monday. We hope that the authorities will come up with more effective measures.

The transparency of governance under meritocracy

Is a panacea for Disease Control and Prevention

Tracy Yao, jewelry designer, 40, Singapore

I spend half the year in Singapore, where my husband is based and my children go to school here. On January 16, she went to Singapore with a group. The others went back in the early morning of the 21st, the same day that academician Zhong Nanshan announced the "human-to-human" policy.

We felt very lucky at that time. We had discussed with our partners whether the tour was years ago or years later. If it was years later, the loss would be very heavy, because the mainland would ask the travel agency here in Singapore to return the advance payment, but the travel agency has already paid the advance to the Singapore hotel, many engage in the traveling small and medium-sized enterprise not to be possible.

Singapore is doing well. Yesterday there were 13 new cases, bringing the total to 200. For a country with a population of more than 5 million, the control measures should be well controlled if they are not particularly stringent. I think the most important reason is that we cut off the input channel very early, the government works very transparently, gives people a lot of confidence, everything is in order.

Singapore Image / Visual China

The prime minister made a speech in early February, and two days before that he made a public speech calling on people to do their jobs, not to panic and to give precious medical resources to the seriously ill. Singapore will also refrain from measures such as the closure of the city, but is expected to step up measures to test ahead of time to prepare Singaporeans.

Although society as a whole is relatively stable, but Singapore is a pluralistic country, there have been several clusters of infection, church meetings, military clubs and so on, the government can do more is the initiative, small gatherings are not strictly controlled. In addition, the power of religion can not be underestimated. The other day a strange thing happened, a government minister gathered 200 people to hold an anti-epidemic conference, very strange operation.

I think countermeasures have a lot to do with national conditions. Singapore is a meritocracy, society is very rational, management is very transparent, there is a pair of Wuhan couples false trip in Singapore is controlled, everyone will talk about your integrity problem. A PR (permanent resident) was deported because he refused to be quarantined in his home, refused to answer his phone, and was disqualified from permanent residence when the authorities issued an injunction, which is not tolerated in Singapore.

The second is that Singapore's resources are too scarce to cause panic. Throughout, the Singapore government has not advised people to wear masks, saying you need to wear them only if you are sick, not if you are not sick, leaving masks for those who need them more. One day there were new cases, and the supermarket ran out of rice, but the next day more rice was on the shelves, meaning people knew that supplies were plentiful, and then there was no more looting, except for masks.

With the leaders taking the lead in lowering salaries and the prime minister's wife making their voices heard on social media, the people have great confidence in the government and the anti-epidemic measures are well implemented. I don't think the epidemic will break out in Singapore.

However, the economy will still be hit hard, and the tourism industry has suffered heavy losses. It is said that the number of tourists visiting tourist attractions has dropped by 90% in the past few days. Some tourist attractions are even free to attract tourists. There is also a 30% to 40% loss in the number of hotel guests, the airline industry, the retail industry, the shipping industry will be greatly affected.

Seoul, South Korea, still commuting

Has hit the industry hard

Wang Ying, 25, a South Korean student, Seoul, South Korea

My School is in Seoul, Korea. Fearing that South Korea would not allow the Chinese to enter, I returned to Seoul early, quarantined myself for two weeks, and stayed at Seoul's home when the outbreak flared up. Later, the Korean epidemic gradually serious, the school also changed to teach online, I decided to return to the country. I recently returned to the United States and am currently under quarantine.

South Korea has about 8,000 confirmed cases, growing at a rate of more than 800 a day. Seoul still commutes to work, and public areas are equipped with infrared thermometers and sanitizers. But schools have delayed the start of the school year, some large-scale places are closed for the day and face masks are "hard to find" . Supplies and transportation are basically the same as usual, but South Korea's film and television industry has been hit hard because they are shooting on the fly, and some of the shows that have already been aired are hard to stop because of the epidemic.

South Korea is a country that worships religious freedom, and in the early days of the epidemic, people still attended church services (including New World Churches) . At first some people questioned them, I think because they did not understand the severity of the epidemic early on. China has paid a heavy price to make people understand the severity of the virus, but we can not deny everything about religion just because we see the possibility of the virus spreading in the early stages of the epidemic. What I do know is that the church in Seoul has completely abolished worship, has been preaching about how to prevent the virus, and is actively providing masks to the community around the church, which is a spontaneous act of the church.

Image / visual China

Each country's national conditions, systems, economic conditions are different, it is difficult to copy each other. China has been able to exert such control, not only for institutional reasons, but also because of the basic industrial chain, the abundance of materials, and the strong control of the government.

South Korean media are very direct and not optimistic about the outbreak, local doctors also directly declared that "the worst case scenario in South Korea will be 40% of the people infected. ". Seoul now has more than 100 cases, and Daegu is even less optimistic. But Seoul's friends in Seoul have been saying that Seoul is safe, and many people in Seoul think so, too. Clearly they are not fully aware of the high infectious risk of the virus, nor are they properly aware that Seoul, with its small land area and large population base, is likely to be followed by explosive growth.

From the discovery to the present control, the Korean government has never concealed the truth, is directly to the public to tell the truth, and to warn the public to take precautions. To be honest, I think it's one of the best things the Korean government has ever done. At this point, anything we can do is good. Inaction is the worst. For now, the South Korean government is trying hard.

When the epidemic first broke out in our country, I was angry at what I saw as the lack of respect for human life. As the epidemic grew worse, I turned my anger toward society for its lack of transparency and openness. And then I thought, well, I shouldn't think about it, because in that case, it's probably hard for anyone to make a good judgment. Now, I'm trying to understand.

You have to have a fever for 4 days to qualify for a test

The Japanese epidemic is a mystery

Xiao Yu, Japanese student, 24, Tokyo, Japan

Our school has been closed since February 18. I had planned to return home at the end of February, but at that time, considering the severity of the epidemic in the country, and fearing the risk of infection on the road, I cancelled it. Unexpectedly, Japan is now more serious than the country, it's not so easy to go back to China, there are only Narita International Airport and direct flights to Beijing on this side of Tokyo, and after landing there will be a concentration of quarantine at hotels near the Beijing Airport, so I've given up the idea of going back, it's safer not to go out.

The Japanese epidemic has one word: "mystery. ". It feels like it's about to explode, but the numbers are holding steady. The number of confirmed cases announced now is 1,388. There were 54 new cases the day before yesterday. Tokyo is fine, Hokkaido will be more serious, but in fact there may be more cases. The current attitude in Japan toward the epidemic is very strange, and it feels that if it is not tested, it will be fine, the reason is for fear of causing the country's medical collapse, to leave treatment opportunities to the seriously ill patients. Softbank President Masayoshi Son was so reviled online for donating a $1 million kit that he had to replace it with a donor mask.

In Tokyo, you need to have a fever of 37.5 degrees for four days in a row to qualify for a test, but you don't have to be tested, so if you do get an infection, you'll have to delay getting it. While mild illness is recommended at home isolation treatment, but no one forced you to rely entirely on self-awareness, some people with a fever will go to work. Therefore, the current number of confirmed cases in Japan is estimated to be less than the actual number of infections.

However, the Japanese people have begun to pay attention to it recently. I live here in Ikebukuro, Tokyo. Every time I go to the supermarket, it seems that 60% of the people wear masks. Today I went to Shibuya, it is estimated that more than 80% wear masks, mainly because of the princess cruise ship, the domestic situation in Japan has become much more serious. We had personal lessons and skills tests given by teachers after the holidays, which have been cancelled, Japanese schools are mostly closed, and some companies allow employees to apply to work from home.

The government has introduced measures such as a ban on gatherings of more than 100 people, shorter hours at tourist sites, but less stringent, and places such as Kyoto do not comply. In the past, people also scolded the government on the Internet. They felt that the incident of the princess had not been handled well. However, after being persuaded by the government, they began to "self-cultivate the Leek" and followed the government's advice. After all, the Japanese people did not know in their hearts, because they don't test for it.

The outbreak has hit the Japanese economy hard, with a sharp drop in tourists, the country's mainly tertiary sector of the economy, and the disruption of global supply chains and falling consumer demand, as well as traditional manufacturing industries like electronics and cars. Why is the Japanese government so obsessed with the Olympics? It was supposed to be a gamble on national luck and boost the economy, but it turned out to be such a big one.

Although the situation is grim, but the overall quality of the Japanese people, there is no excessive panic, in addition to grab empty toilet paper, there has been no disturbance. They were really scared of a medical run, but on the other hand, I thought it would be reassuring to get tested, not to wonder if I was, and then move around and become a mobile source of infection. So I'm a little less understanding and a little more concerned.

From top to bottom, it's spreading

Tourism has been completely suspended

Sun Jie, founder of Yazid Perth Chinese restaurant

34 Yazd, Iran

The Iranian side of the epidemic is now affected from top to bottom, many people in the government have been infected with the virus, Iran did not pay attention before, do not wear masks, resulting in mutual infection.

I came to Iran in April 2019, originally intending to return home after Chinese New Year, but now I can't because of the domestic epidemic. The true death toll in Iran is said to be higher than reported in the news.

The death toll is increasing. Recently, on the Social Media News, I also saw that the doctor said that the patient's condition was very serious. More than 10 days ago, he went to the drug store to buy a mask, and it was only then that everyone slowly realized the seriousness of the epidemic, start wearing masks. Schools have been closed since 10 days ago, and all but a few grocery stores have been closed, as have my bed-and-breakfast and Chinese restaurants. On March 11th the government issued a notice saying that from March 12th, people should not leave their homes for three days.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Closed restaurants and hotels, source / interviewee

March 21 is the Iranian New Year, the Chinese equivalent of Spring Festival. Iranians like to travel elsewhere in the new year, I heard last year at this time can not get room, the government opened a mosque and schools to receive tourists, but now there are almost no tourists, everyone lost business.

A lot of Iranians think the Chinese brought the virus here, and they're a little hostile to the Chinese. Students in Tehran say they are now afraid to leave their homes for fear of being threatened by locals. I once met a man shouting "US" at me on the way to a restaurant and saw people talking about it.

During the Chinese New Year, when the epidemic had not yet broken out here, many tourists bought masks and returned home. The government also donated many masks to China. However, the production capacity here is not enough and the medical care level is not very good. Now, China has sent experts to come here, masks and protective equipment will also be donated, and the epidemic may be brought under control.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Shops have been closed on the streets, sources / interviewees

Iranians think wearing a mask means you're sick, not protection. Iranians don't like to wash their hands. Government news reports say you must wear a mask and better wear gloves, but many people don't care either. People on this side, because of their faith, think it's okay to be sick, and their God will protect them. I also saw on the television news that some of the older people said that God would bless them.

In Iran, as in Europe, people kiss and shake hands. Iranians also like to have dinner and tea together. There are many families in Iran. Things have been a little better lately, and everyone's greeting has been changed to a fist bump. Now, when we go to the supermarket, the staff will spray everyone's hands with disinfectant and hand out a pair of disposable gloves. This is a good thing, but I feel that the government needs to continue to publicize the seriousness of the epidemic, let everyone know about this.
